\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The COVID-19 pandemic spread across countries and regions through complex spatial and temporal processes.
 In the Netherlands,
 the epidemic unfolded unevenly across municipalities,
 with some areas experiencing early outbreaks while others saw delayed increases in infection counts,
 a pattern observed in many countries during the COVID-19 pandemic (Kraemer et al.,
 2020).
 Understanding how such epidemics propagate across space is important for evaluating public health responses and for improving epidemiological modelling.
 One concept frequently used to describe the spatial spread of innovations and diseases is hierarchical diffusion,
 where processes initially spread through highly connected urban centres before gradually reaching smaller or more peripheral regions (Hägerstrand,
 1967;
 Rogers,
 2003).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hierarchical diffusion is particularly relevant for infectious diseases because human mobility networks and population density strongly influence transmission dynamics (Balcan et al.,
 2009;
 Brockmann & Helbing,
 2013).
 Large cities often act as hubs of connectivity,
 with greater international travel,
 higher population densities,
 and more intensive social interaction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a result,
 epidemics may first intensify in these urban areas before spreading outward to smaller municipalities.
 Detecting such spatial patterns requires analytical approaches capable of comparing epidemic trajectories across many locations simultaneously.
 The Netherlands provides a useful case study for examining such processes because its dense urban network and high levels of regional mobility create strong spatial connectivity between municipalities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Time-series analysis provides a natural framework for studying epidemic dynamics.
 Municipality-level COVID-19 case counts form temporal sequences that reflect the progression of infection waves over time.
 However,
 comparing hundreds of time series directly is challenging because epidemic curves may differ in magnitude,
 timing,
 and noise levels.
 Time-series clustering methods provide a useful solution by grouping municipalities that exhibit similar temporal epidemic patterns (Liao,
 2005).
 By identifying clusters of similar epidemic trajectories,
 it becomes possible to detect typical temporal profiles,
 such as early-peaking,
 intermediate,
 or delayed epidemic patterns.
 When combined with spatial mapping of cluster membership,
 these patterns can reveal whether epidemics spread through hierarchical or geographically structured diffusion processes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While many studies analyse national epidemic dynamics,
 fewer studies examine how municipality-level epidemic trajectories cluster temporally and spatially.
 Understanding these local patterns is important for identifying how epidemics propagate through regional mobility and settlement networks.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this project,
 clustering techniques are applied to municipality-level COVID-19 time series from two different sources.
 The first dataset consists of observed case counts reported by the Dutch National Institute for Public Health and the Environment (RIVM).
 These data provide a record of how the epidemic evolved across Dutch municipalities over multiple waves of infection.
 The second dataset is generated by an agent-based model (ABM) of COVID-19 transmission.
 Agent-based models simulate disease spread by representing individuals and their interactions,
 allowing researchers to explore how behavioural patterns and contact networks influence epidemic outcomes (Epstein,
 2009).
 The ABM produces simulated infection counts at the municipality level,
 which can be analysed in a manner similar to the real data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Comparing the observed RIVM data with the simulated ABM output provides an opportunity to evaluate how well the model reproduces real epidemic dynamics.
 If the model realistically captures transmission processes and spatial interactions,
 the temporal clustering patterns observed in the simulation should resemble those found in the real data.
 Conversely,
 substantial differences between the two datasets may indicate limitations in the model structure or assumptions.
 Such comparisons are therefore useful for assessing the realism and explanatory power of epidemiological simulations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To investigate these issues,
 the analysis follows a reproducible workflow that includes data restructuring,
 preprocessing,
 time-series segmentation,
 and clustering of municipality-level epidemic trajectories.
 The clustering results are then interpreted both temporally and spatially in order to identify possible diffusion patterns.
 Finally,
 the observed and simulated clustering structures are compared to evaluate the extent to which the model reproduces the spatial and temporal organisation of the real epidemic.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study is guided by three research questions:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What temporal patterns appear in municipality-level COVID-19 time series in the Netherlands?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Do RIVM observations and ABM simulations produce similar or different clustering structures?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Do the resulting clusters provide evidence of hierarchical diffusion in the spread of COVID-19 across municipalities?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By addressing these questions,
 the analysis aims to improve understanding of spatial epidemic dynamics and to assess the extent to which agent-based simulations can reproduce the temporal and geographical patterns observed in real epidemic data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Data and study material
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
RIVM data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first dataset used in this study consists of municipality-level COVID-19 case counts reported by the Dutch National Institute for Public Health and the Environment (RIVM).
 These data provide an empirical record of the progression of the COVID-19 epidemic across municipalities in the Netherlands and allow construction of epidemic trajectories for individual locations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The original RIVM data are provided in a long tabular format in which each row corresponds to a municipality–date combination.
 For time-series analysis and clustering,
 the data were restructured into a municipality × time matrix,
 where each row represents a municipality and each column corresponds to a time step in the epidemic.
 Each row therefore forms a time series describing the evolution of COVID-19 cases for that municipality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dataset covers the main period of the epidemic in the Netherlands,
 beginning in February 2020 and extending into 2023.
 After restructuring and aggregation,
 the time series contain approximately 150 weekly observations per municipality.
 Weekly aggregation was used to reduce reporting noise and ensure comparability with the temporal resolution used in the simulation outputs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following preprocessing,
 the dataset includes 342 municipalities with complete or near-complete time series used for clustering analysis of observed epidemic dynamics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
ABM simulation data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second dataset consists of outputs generated by an agent-based model (ABM) simulating the spread of COVID-19 in the Netherlands.
 Agent-based models represent individuals as agents interacting within a simulated environment,
 allowing epidemic dynamics to emerge from behavioural interactions and contact patterns.
 Such models are commonly used to explore the effects of interventions,
 mobility patterns,
 and contact structures on disease transmission.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the simulation used for this study,
 infection counts are recorded at the municipality level over time.
 Similar to the RIVM data,
 the ABM output was transformed into a municipality × time matrix,
 where each municipality is represented by a time series of simulated infection counts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ABM dataset contains approximately 396 municipalities,
 reflecting the spatial resolution used in the simulation environment.
 Simulation outputs provide infection counts at regular time intervals and were aggregated to weekly values to ensure comparability with the RIVM dataset.
 This step allows both datasets to be analysed using the same temporal resolution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resulting time series capture the modelled epidemic trajectory for each municipality and enable comparison between observed epidemic patterns and simulated dynamics.
 
\end_layout

