\begin_layout Section
Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All data preprocessing,
 clustering procedures,
 and visualisations were implemented in Python and documented in the accompanying analysis notebook.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Data architecture and preprocessing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To enable comparison between observed and simulated epidemic dynamics,
 both datasets were organised into a consistent municipality × time matrix structure.
 In this format,
 each row represents a municipality and each column represents a time step,
 allowing infections to be analysed as time series for each spatial unit.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The original RIVM dataset was provided in long format,
 where each record contained a municipality identifier,
 date,
 and reported number of COVID-19 cases.
 For time-series analysis,
 the data were reshaped using a pivot operation so that municipalities formed the rows and weekly time steps formed the columns.
 This produced a matrix in which each row represents the epidemic trajectory of a municipality across the observation period.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ABM simulation output contained infection counts generated by the agent-based model for multiple municipalities.
 Although its structure differed slightly from the observational dataset,
 it was reorganised into the same municipality × time matrix to ensure compatibility with the analytical pipeline used for the RIVM data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After restructuring,
 preprocessing was applied to reduce noise and emphasise epidemic patterns.
 Weekly infection counts may fluctuate because of reporting delays or stochastic simulation effects.
 A rolling mean smoothing procedure was therefore applied to each municipality time series to reduce short-term variability while preserving overall epidemic trends.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 the time series were normalised using z-score standardisation.
 This ensures clustering focuses on the temporal shape of epidemic trajectories rather than differences in magnitude between municipalities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Segmentation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Epidemic processes often occur in multiple waves rather than as a single continuous outbreak.
 To account for this structure,
 the analysis incorporated temporal segmentation based on epidemic waves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wave detection was performed using the national epidemic curve,
 obtained by aggregating infection counts across all municipalities.
 The national curve provides a high-level representation of the overall epidemic progression and makes major peaks and troughs in infection levels clearly visible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the smoothed national curve,
 major epidemic phases were identified by examining the timing of peaks and transitions between periods of rising and declining case numbers.
 These turning points were used to define analysis segments corresponding to different epidemic waves.
 Each segment therefore represents a period during which the epidemic followed a relatively coherent temporal pattern across the country.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Segmenting the epidemic into waves serves two purposes.
 First,
 it allows clustering algorithms to focus on specific epidemic phases,
 which may reveal patterns that are less visible when analysing the entire time series.
 Second,
 segmentation makes it possible to compare how municipalities behaved during different waves,
 highlighting variations in the timing or intensity of local outbreaks.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both the full time series and wave-based segments were considered in the analysis to evaluate how segmentation affects clustering results and interpretability.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Clustering methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To identify groups of municipalities with similar epidemic trajectories,
 two time-series clustering approaches were considered:
 K-Shape clustering and Self-Organising Maps (SOM).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
K-Shape clustering is specifically designed for time-series data and uses shape-based similarity measures to group time series according to the form of their temporal patterns.
 The method aligns time series by maximising the similarity of their shapes,
 making it particularly suitable for analysing epidemic curves where the timing and structure of peaks are more important than absolute magnitude.
 K-Shape therefore emphasises similarities in the progression of epidemic waves across municipalities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to K-Shape,
 Self-Organising Maps (SOM) were explored as an alternative clustering approach.
 SOM is an unsupervised neural network algorithm that projects high-dimensional data onto a lower-dimensional grid while preserving topological relationships between observations.
 In the context of time-series analysis,
 SOM can reveal clusters of municipalities with similar temporal patterns while also providing an interpretable visual representation of the clustering structure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two clustering methods rely on different similarity concepts.
 K-Shape focuses on shape-based similarity,
 typically derived from cross-correlation between time series,
 while SOM commonly uses Euclidean distance in the transformed feature space.
 Because Euclidean distance is sensitive to magnitude differences,
 the z-score normalisation step described earlier was important to ensure that clustering primarily reflected temporal patterns rather than absolute case counts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By applying different clustering approaches and similarity measures,
 the analysis evaluates how methodological choices influence the identification of epidemic patterns.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cluster selection and visualisation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important step in clustering analysis is determining the appropriate number of clusters.
 Rather than fixing this number in advance,
 several candidate solutions were tested with cluster numbers ranging from three to six.
 This range balances the need to identify meaningful patterns while avoiding overly fragmented cluster structures.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To evaluate these candidate solutions,
 both quantitative and qualitative criteria were used.
 The silhouette score,
 a commonly used internal evaluation metric,
 was applied to measure the separation between clusters and the cohesion of observations within each cluster.
 Higher silhouette scores indicate better-defined clusters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 numerical metrics alone are not always sufficient for time-series clustering,
 particularly in epidemiological applications where interpretability is important.
 Cluster solutions were therefore also evaluated based on the interpretability of temporal profiles.
 Centroid curves were examined to determine whether clusters represented distinct epidemic trajectories,
 such as early,
 intermediate,
 or late epidemic peaks.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Spatial coherence was also considered.
 After clustering,
 municipalities were mapped to assess whether clusters displayed meaningful geographic patterns,
 such as concentrations in urban regions or peripheral areas.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By combining silhouette scores,
 centroid interpretability,
 and spatial coherence,
 a final clustering configuration was selected for both the RIVM and ABM datasets.
 
\end_layout

