\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section interprets the clustering results in relation to spatial diffusion theory,
 epidemic modelling,
 and methodological considerations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Evidence for hierarchical diffusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The clustering analysis of the RIVM dataset reveals differences in the timing and structure of epidemic trajectories across municipalities.
 The centroid curves show that epidemic peaks did not occur simultaneously across the country.
 Instead,
 clusters exhibit staggered peaks,
 with some municipalities experiencing earlier increases in infection counts while others show delayed trajectories.
 This pattern indicates temporal heterogeneity in how the epidemic progressed across municipalities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such staggered dynamics are consistent with hierarchical diffusion.
 In this framework,
 infections initially intensify in highly connected urban centres that function as transmission hubs within mobility networks.
 From these centres,
 the epidemic spreads outward through human movement and interaction,
 gradually reaching smaller settlements.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spatial distribution of clusters supports this interpretation.
 Earlier-peaking clusters appear more frequently in the highly urbanised Randstad region,
 where mobility connectivity and population density are high,
 while later-peaking clusters occur more often in peripheral municipalities.
 These results suggest epidemic propagation followed patterns consistent with hierarchical diffusion through urban connectivity networks.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Real and simulated epidemic structure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Comparison of the clustering results reveals important differences between the empirical epidemic patterns observed in the RIVM data and those produced by the agent-based model.
 In the RIVM dataset,
 the centroid curves display clear variation in the timing of epidemic peaks between clusters.
 Different groups of municipalities experienced epidemic waves at different moments,
 producing a staggered temporal pattern across the country and indicating substantial temporal heterogeneity in epidemic progression.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In contrast,
 the centroid curves derived from the ABM simulation show a more synchronised structure.
 Epidemic peaks occur within similar time windows across clusters,
 with only modest variation in peak magnitude.
 Spatial patterns are also weaker,
 with clusters distributed more evenly across municipalities rather than forming distinct regional groupings.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One possible explanation is that the simulation assumes relatively homogeneous mobility or contact structures between municipalities.
 If interaction rates or mobility connections are represented too uniformly,
 infections can propagate through the network more evenly,
 producing synchronised epidemic waves.
 Simplified assumptions about contact mixing or demographic variation may further reduce local differences in epidemic timing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These results suggest that while the ABM captures general epidemic waves,
 it may underrepresent regional diffusion dynamics observed in real epidemic data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Methodological implications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Methodological choices influenced the interpretability of the clustering results.
 First,
 smoothing of municipality-level time series reduced short-term fluctuations caused by reporting delays and local variability.
 Weekly COVID-19 case counts often contain noise that obscures epidemic trends,
 and applying a rolling mean filter made the broader structure of epidemic waves clearer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Normalisation using a z-score transformation was also essential.
 Municipalities differ greatly in population size and case counts,
 which can dominate clustering results.
 Standardisation ensured that clustering focused on the timing and shape of epidemic trajectories rather than magnitude.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Temporal segmentation of the epidemic into major waves further improved clustering clarity.
 Analysing epidemic phases allowed the clustering algorithm to detect differences in municipal behaviour during specific waves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 the K-Shape algorithm proved suitable because it groups time series based on similarity in temporal shape,
 making it appropriate for analysing epidemic curves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Limitations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several limitations should be considered when interpreting these results.
 First,
 early stages of the COVID-19 pandemic in the Netherlands were affected by limited testing capacity.
 Consequently,
 reported RIVM case counts likely underestimate true infection levels during initial waves,
 which may influence the observed trajectories.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second,
 vaccination dynamics were not incorporated in the analysis.
 Increasing vaccination coverage during later phases of the pandemic may have influenced infection patterns and the timing of later waves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third,
 the analysis was conducted at the municipality level.
 Aggregating data at this scale may conceal finer spatial transmission patterns within municipalities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 clustering outcomes depend on the chosen number of clusters.
 Different values of k could produce alternative grouping structures and different interpretations of epidemic trajectories.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Recommendations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Future analyses of epidemic diffusion could be improved in several ways.
 Using population-adjusted incidence rates instead of raw case counts would improve comparability between municipalities,
 while incorporating vaccination dynamics would better capture changing population susceptibility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Methodologically,
 similarity measures such as Dynamic Time Warping (DTW) and network-based clustering could better represent temporal shifts and spatial connectivity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From a modelling perspective,
 incorporating mobility networks and greater spatial heterogeneity in the ABM may produce more realistic regional diffusion patterns.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study analysed municipality-level COVID-19 time series in the Netherlands using time-series clustering to investigate spatial diffusion patterns and compare empirical epidemic data with agent-based model (ABM) simulations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The clustering results from the RIVM dataset revealed clear temporal heterogeneity in epidemic trajectories across municipalities.
 Distinct clusters showed differences in the timing and intensity of epidemic waves,
 with some municipalities experiencing earlier peaks than others.
 The spatial distribution of these clusters suggests that earlier trajectories occurred more often in highly connected urban regions,
 while later trajectories appeared more frequently in peripheral municipalities.
 These patterns are consistent with hierarchical diffusion,
 in which infections spread progressively from major urban centres to smaller settlements.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ABM simulation reproduced some epidemic dynamics but generated more synchronised trajectories across municipalities than those observed in the empirical data.
 Cluster centroid curves indicate that epidemic peaks occurred within similar time windows across simulated clusters,
 reflecting weaker temporal variation than in the empirical data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Methodologically,
 the results show that preprocessing strongly influences clustering outcomes.
 Wave-based segmentation combined with smoothing and z-score normalisation produced the most interpretable trajectory clusters by highlighting epidemic wave structure while reducing noise.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These findings highlight the importance of incorporating realistic mobility structures and spatial heterogeneity when using agent-based models to simulate epidemic diffusion.
 
\end_layout

